An Overview of Unit Testing and TDD

The tests we write in this module are accessibility-focused Unit Tests.

As the name suggests, each test is concerned with making sure that one small piece (or “unit”) of a component behaves as expected.

How granular do you want to get?

Looking at components in isolation is a theme that carries over from Storybook, which can help us plan out the tests we are going to write.

For example, the ListingExcerpt component features an image. This means we could write a unit test that ensures it includes an alt attribute.

We changed the DropdownList to use a button instead of a div, so we could write a unit test to ensure it remains focusable and operable with the keyboard.

There is some subjectivity to the scope of tests to write.

The date picker component is made up several subcomponents. What functionality should you test? Do you need to write tests for every button?

Think about the variations in your components, how behavior changes, and what the most important functionality is.

Ultimately, the goal is to prevent regressions from happening and baking in functionality that makes sure a component is accessible and won’t break.

Jest and Testing Library

The tools we will use for accessibility-focused unit testing are Jest and Testing Library.

Jest is a framework that includes several different tools related to automated testing.

Testing Library is a “family of packages” that pair nicely with Jest and other tools. We’ll use jest-dom, as well as react-testing-library for testing the CampSpots app.

We will follow the Test-Driven Development (TDD) approach when writing tests:

  1. Select a component to test.
  2. Write a test describing the behavior that fails accessibility requirements.
  3. Make the test pass by fixing the accessibility problems in the component.

Test Scripts inside of package.json

Jest and Testing Library are both pre-configured in our workshop demo project.

Inside of package.json is a script called test that runs Jest on any test file found in the components and exercise1-jest directories:

"scripts": {
	...
  "test": "jest components/* exercise1-jest/*",
  ...
}
"scripts": {
	...
  "test": "jest components/* exercise1-jest/*",
  ...
}

Notice that there are additional “test” scripts that we will see in later modules.

These scripts have been configured separately because Jest is smart enough to find and run any test files it finds in our project, which isn’t exactly what we want.

Jest Configuration

At the bottom of package.json is a Jest-specific configuration section under the jest key.

We have set up Jest to look for js and jsx files in the correct project directories.

Also notice the transform configuration that adds additional functionality to Jest. In this setup we are enabling the latest JavaScript features with some help from Babel, as well as CSS variables and Sass support thanks to jest-transform-css.

An Overview of Project Structure

The structure of our unit tests in this project is similar to widely-used conventions.

Inside of the main components directory is a subdirectory named for the specific component code it contains associated files for. Then inside of the component-specific subdirectory is a __tests__ directory that has the test files.

If the component is a single file, it may have tests inside of components/__tests__ instead of being in a subdirectory.

The naming convention you follow for the test files is up to your team. It is common to include .test.js or .spec.js in the filename, but Jest doesn’t require it.

📝 Exercise: Add Jest & Testing Library to your own project

Following the example configuration in the workshop repo, add Jest and Testing library.

Configure the test scripts in package.json and structure your components directory to prepare for writing tests.
